  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 8:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐλυμαίνετο",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": deponent verb, used in classical Greek of personal outrage (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "λύμη",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), of scourging and torturing, of outraging the dead, of the ruin and devastation caused by an army (Wetstein). In the LXX it is found several times, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cf.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " especially Psalms 79(80):13, of a wild boar ravaging a vineyard, and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cf.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " also ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Sir 28:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". As the word is used only by St. Luke it is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "possible",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " that it may have been suggested by its frequent employment in medical language, where it is employed not only of injury by wrong treatment, but also of the ravages of disease, Hobart, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Medical Language",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", pp. 211, 212. R.V. renders “laid waste,” A.V. (so Tyndale) “made havoc of,” but the revisers have rendered ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "πορθέω",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " by the latter, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cf.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 9:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
